96
00:04:26,606 --> 00:04:28,368
And so what people usually mean in this case

97
00:04:28,408 --> 00:04:29,708
is that they don't like cinematics.

98
00:04:30,329 --> 00:04:31,890
And I think because you guys are here,

99
00:04:31,910 --> 00:04:34,492
you know that there's more to game writing than cinematics.

100
00:04:34,532 --> 00:04:37,294
So a lot of the time, what I try to establish on a team

101
00:04:37,314 --> 00:04:38,375
that I've come into, that there's

102
00:04:38,415 --> 00:04:40,496
a difference between cinematics and game writing.

103
00:04:41,277 --> 00:04:42,838
And what I like to say that game writing is

104
00:04:42,878 --> 00:04:43,779
is sort of a bridge.

105
00:04:44,099 --> 00:04:46,440
It's a bridge between what the designers intended

106
00:04:46,540 --> 00:04:49,182
and what stories the players are telling themselves.

107
00:04:50,334 --> 00:04:52,275
As writers, we're there to empower the players,

108
00:04:52,295 --> 00:04:54,576
to make them feel like their choices have meaning,

109
00:04:54,756 --> 00:04:56,657
even though the designers have something

110
00:04:56,758 --> 00:04:58,498
very definite in mind for what the writers,

111
00:04:58,739 --> 00:05:00,099
or what the players will experience.

112
00:05:01,980 --> 00:05:03,461
Great, I'm gonna take that a step further.

113
00:05:03,501 --> 00:05:05,942
The term that I would like to define is emergent narrative,

114
00:05:06,042 --> 00:05:07,843
which has several different meanings

115
00:05:07,883 --> 00:05:08,984
depending on who you talk to.

116
00:05:09,424 --> 00:05:12,086
My favorite is that 50% of the story

117
00:05:12,146 --> 00:05:13,506
is told in the player's head.

118
00:05:14,324 --> 00:05:18,247
So part of writing for games is leaving those silences where the player can talk to themselves

119
00:05:18,307 --> 00:05:22,091
without even realizing and say, oh, that's what this means, this is what it means to me.

120
00:05:22,771 --> 00:05:26,314
Because they're going to tell themselves a far more personal story than we can ever tell them

121
00:05:26,374 --> 00:05:27,795
since we're writing for a mass audience.

122
00:05:28,476 --> 00:05:30,878
And that was one of my favorite things about working on Tides of Numenera

123
00:05:30,898 --> 00:05:33,200
was the ability to have that ambiguity

124
00:05:33,660 --> 00:05:36,483
and present the players with the option to interpret what was going on.

125
00:05:37,063 --> 00:05:37,984
and react accordingly.

126
00:05:38,445 --> 00:05:41,088
So remembering that the player is telling the story with you

127
00:05:41,508 --> 00:05:44,031
even though you're far apart in time or in space,

128
00:05:44,432 --> 00:05:45,873
they're still a part of that story

129
00:05:45,994 --> 00:05:48,376
and what they create out of what you have given them

130
00:05:49,097 --> 00:05:50,158
is very, very exciting.

131
00:05:52,752 --> 00:05:56,613
So in my ever increasing effort to make sure Leanne never invites me on the panels again,

132
00:05:57,674 --> 00:06:01,656
when I initially got this question, I went through a range of emotions, much like dialogue

133
00:06:01,696 --> 00:06:02,236
responses.

134
00:06:02,376 --> 00:06:06,578
I went from the angry, well, there's terms I never like to hear, like the word impossible.

135
00:06:06,878 --> 00:06:09,799
If you ever tell me the word impossible, I'm going to kill you until you quantify it.

136
00:06:10,360 --> 00:06:11,880
Also the word sorry offends me.

137
00:06:12,200 --> 00:06:15,762
And also, we need to be on the same page when I ask for something by the end of the day,

138
00:06:15,782 --> 00:06:18,423
I need to confirm with you what end of the day means.

139
00:06:18,814 --> 00:06:24,338
But from a narrative standpoint, I like to invent a term when talking with QA,

140
00:06:24,398 --> 00:06:29,201
because I feel quality assurance has been trained never to report a story-based bug.

141
00:06:29,882 --> 00:06:32,564
They always treat it as a deep priority suggestion or,

142
00:06:32,944 --> 00:06:34,865
man, you know, this is kind of confusing to me,

143
00:06:34,885 --> 00:06:37,808
but I'm kind of afraid to bring it up because story is kind of nebulous.

144
00:06:38,248 --> 00:06:39,629
For me, a narrative bug.

145
00:06:40,149 --> 00:06:41,750
is a very, very real thing.

146
00:06:41,890 --> 00:06:43,932
If there is some story point you don't get,

147
00:06:43,952 --> 00:06:46,233
if you don't understand how a character

148
00:06:46,293 --> 00:06:47,614
arrived at a certain location,

149
00:06:47,654 --> 00:06:49,696
even how you as a player got to a location,

150
00:06:50,096 --> 00:06:52,037
and it's never explained anywhere else in the game,

151
00:06:52,538 --> 00:06:54,940
those are things that QA should be trained to write up,

152
00:06:55,620 --> 00:06:57,661
along with really bad VO lines

153
00:06:57,681 --> 00:07:00,223
that the QA department will laugh about consistently.

154
00:07:00,663 --> 00:07:02,725
Walk through your QA department, listen,

155
00:07:02,965 --> 00:07:04,286
see where your bad VO is,

156
00:07:04,366 --> 00:07:05,887
and either delete it or get it re-recorded.

157
00:07:08,831 --> 00:07:14,554
So the term, I guess it's less of a term and it's more of a distinction, is story versus setting.

158
00:07:15,075 --> 00:07:18,516
And I probably don't really need to define these for this room, but I'll kind of give my shorthand.

159
00:07:18,597 --> 00:07:23,559
Story is the plot. It's the sequence of events with a beginning, a middle, and an end.

160
00:07:23,619 --> 00:07:26,141
It's usually driven by the player or it's about the player.

161
00:07:26,781 --> 00:07:30,463
The setting, on the other hand, is the backdrop. It's the place and the time.

162
00:07:30,763 --> 00:07:32,484
It's all the details about the world.

163
00:07:32,864 --> 00:07:36,266
It's basically the stuff that would be there even if the player didn't exist.

164
00:07:37,687 --> 00:07:43,752
And as writers we need setting because it helps us to create a coherent and consistent game

165
00:07:44,292 --> 00:07:49,776
But the important point to keep in mind is just because you have a setting doesn't mean you have a story

166
00:07:50,357 --> 00:07:55,881
And that's a distinction that has been lost on a number of teams that I've worked on not so much the teams with these guys

167
00:07:55,921 --> 00:07:59,303
But sometimes in the MMO space that's been that's been misunderstood

168
00:07:59,323 --> 00:08:01,325
Fantastic

169
00:08:02,649 --> 00:08:04,590
So we're going to jump into the first question,

170
00:08:04,650 --> 00:08:07,512
which is relevant to that, so the setting versus the story.

