00:08:08,193 --> 00:08:10,194
How do you balance input from other disciplines

172
00:08:10,274 --> 00:08:11,575
with the story requirements?

173
00:08:13,496 --> 00:08:14,697
Go ahead.

174
00:08:14,717 --> 00:08:17,458
Wow, that bleeds directly from what I was saying earlier.

175
00:08:18,539 --> 00:08:21,100
So as Chris was saying about QA,

176
00:08:21,180 --> 00:08:23,122
we want to request input from other departments.

177
00:08:23,202 --> 00:08:25,083
We want to make sure, as I said,

178
00:08:25,103 --> 00:08:26,644
that they are feeling ownership of this

179
00:08:26,704 --> 00:08:29,626
because they have perspectives on the story that,

180
00:08:30,866 --> 00:08:33,908
We don't have, you're all writers here,

181
00:08:33,968 --> 00:08:37,350
we all know what it is to get too close to a story.

182
00:08:37,550 --> 00:08:43,274
It is almost impossible to have a good overview of it

183
00:08:43,334 --> 00:08:44,915
when you're down in the weeds and you're writing

184
00:08:44,975 --> 00:08:47,076
because you're just seeing tree, tree, tree,

185
00:08:47,176 --> 00:08:49,618
and somebody who is new to it is seeing forest.

186
00:08:50,598 --> 00:08:51,238
Or trash.

187
00:08:51,439 --> 00:08:52,179
Or trash, yeah.

188
00:08:53,140 --> 00:08:53,580
Or a fire.

189
00:08:56,027 --> 00:09:01,212
So what we want is we want to get their input. We want people to come in and say, okay, so

190
00:09:01,773 --> 00:09:07,078
here's what I think this is. Here's a cool idea that I have. Artists, for instance, George

191
00:09:07,098 --> 00:09:12,203
said this in an interview just the other day, artists can provide us with insights into

192
00:09:12,243 --> 00:09:15,366
characters and ideas that we never knew that we were lacking.

193
00:09:16,247 --> 00:09:22,449
We can just say, okay, make something cool and new and they will create something that is so

194
00:09:22,610 --> 00:09:25,991
awesome and neat that we're going to like, oh, you know what, we're going to reorient this

195
00:09:26,031 --> 00:09:33,074
entire level to make something really cool about this. We want input from other teams. At the

196
00:09:33,114 --> 00:09:33,714
same time...

197
00:09:36,195 --> 00:09:41,179
At the same time, we don't want them to feel so much ownership that they're pushing us out and

198
00:09:41,199 --> 00:09:44,381
they're like, you just put the words on the page, writer boy.

199
00:09:44,401 --> 00:09:47,123
You just take the script to the dialogue pass and that's how it gets written.

200
00:09:47,744 --> 00:09:53,308
Exactly. So basically, you know, we want to get their input, but then you've got to filter it and

201
00:09:53,348 --> 00:09:56,570
decide, okay, does this actually match with the themes of the game? Does this match with what

202
00:09:56,590 --> 00:10:02,074
we're trying to do? And is this going to be a valuable piece of input moving forward? And it's

203
00:10:02,094 --> 00:10:05,356
your job as writers to figure out where their input plugs in.

204
00:10:05,937 --> 00:10:13,439
Exactly. It is a question of picking your battles, which is something that I think a lot of writers struggle with at first when they get into game writing.

205
00:10:14,379 --> 00:10:18,501
You have to decide what is crucial to the story. You have to decide what's crucial to the game.

206
00:10:18,701 --> 00:10:28,664
And you have to be willing and aware that when you shut someone down, you are stopping them possibly from ever coming to you with an idea again, and you will possibly lose something very precious.

207
00:10:29,577 --> 00:10:31,920
So I would say, once again, pick your battles.

208
00:10:32,360 --> 00:10:36,025
Make sure that if you're going to tell someone that their

209
00:10:36,065 --> 00:10:39,809
idea won't work, and I would advise against that, tell them

210
00:10:39,930 --> 00:10:42,933
why, make them feel part ownership of the project, make

211
00:10:42,953 --> 00:10:43,594
them understand it.

212
00:10:43,634 --> 00:10:45,997
It's an education, or it's an educating moment.

213
00:10:46,873 --> 00:10:48,034
And it can be an ego thing.

214
00:10:48,054 --> 00:10:49,656
If you've worked really hard on an idea

215
00:10:49,716 --> 00:10:50,877
and someone comes in and says, you know,

216
00:10:50,977 --> 00:10:51,877
I don't understand it.

217
00:10:52,518 --> 00:10:53,539
And you try to explain it to them

218
00:10:53,599 --> 00:10:54,599
and they still don't get it,

219
00:10:54,920 --> 00:10:56,521
that's the point where you need to say, okay,

220
00:10:56,621 --> 00:10:58,783
but this person is representative of my audience

221
00:10:58,863 --> 00:11:00,864
just as I am representative of my own audience.

222
00:11:01,344 --> 00:11:02,305
Things that resonate with me

223
00:11:02,325 --> 00:11:04,227
won't necessarily resonate with everyone else.

224
00:11:04,447 --> 00:11:05,988
And so finding that medium between

225
00:11:06,388 --> 00:11:08,790
what they are looking for in the story that you're telling

226
00:11:08,930 --> 00:11:11,292
and how you're telling the story is a delicate balance.

227
00:11:11,717 --> 00:11:16,041
Although, I would add that I did get input from somebody once and they're like, well,

228
00:11:16,061 --> 00:11:20,525
you know what, I don't like the direction this story's going and here's some ideas that

229
00:11:20,545 --> 00:11:21,165
I would have to fix.

230
00:11:21,205 --> 00:11:24,929
It's like, well, that's good, but this is a philosophical RPG, not a...

231
00:11:25,069 --> 00:11:29,012
Yeah, we used to have the three critique rule, like it's okay if one person brings it up,

232
00:11:29,032 --> 00:11:32,676
it's good to digest that, but then it takes two more people to bring up the same subject

233
00:11:32,696 --> 00:11:34,737
and you're like, yeah, that's definitely got to change.

234
00:11:36,733 --> 00:11:38,354
Fantastic. Okay.

