George, would you like to start off?

240
00:11:47,047 --> 00:11:53,751
Sure. So in my opinion, flexibility can really be a mindset. Think of, especially when you're

241
00:11:53,771 --> 00:11:58,534
writing a story, think of everything that you're writing as early on in the project as not

242
00:11:58,594 --> 00:12:04,998
complete. So when you're actually, this is a little goofy, but almost think of a story like a

243
00:12:05,058 --> 00:12:09,721
sculpture. That is at least what I do when I'm coming up with a story for a game. Initially

244
00:12:09,741 --> 00:12:12,923
you've got a big block of stone. It's completely shapeless. It can be anything.

245
00:12:14,144 --> 00:12:18,107
Then, as you're starting to write the initial drafts of the story, it's kind of taking shape,

246
00:12:18,488 --> 00:12:21,070
and you can kind of see what it's going to be, but you've still got a lot of wiggle room,

247
00:12:21,110 --> 00:12:24,213
so when new ideas come up, you can still go in a number of different directions.

248
00:12:24,253 --> 00:12:28,717
And it's only toward the very end of the project, when you've basically got, like, David in

249
00:12:28,757 --> 00:12:35,342
front of you, and you've got a fully formed statue, that it's very difficult to make significant

250
00:12:35,362 --> 00:12:36,243
changes at that point.

251
00:12:37,124 --> 00:12:41,964
Now, having said all that, also, don't be afraid to push back,

252
00:12:42,104 --> 00:12:46,745
especially late in the project, against changes that you feel are too extreme.

253
00:12:47,526 --> 00:12:52,807
But do it in the language of the producers, which means do it in terms of time estimates.

254
00:12:52,947 --> 00:12:56,467
If you think somebody, you're close to the end of a project, and someone says,

255
00:12:56,987 --> 00:12:59,428
oh man, we really want to completely change the beginning of the game.

256
00:12:59,748 --> 00:13:01,828
At that point, instead of...

257
00:13:02,568 --> 00:13:08,090
going crazy, sit down and figure out exactly what the impacts of that is going to be in

258
00:13:08,130 --> 00:13:08,911
terms of days.

259
00:13:09,291 --> 00:13:12,832
So okay, we have to rewrite these 20 dialogues, that's 80 days.

260
00:13:12,912 --> 00:13:14,813
We have to change these levels, that's another 20.

261
00:13:15,413 --> 00:13:19,615
Whatever it is, and then get, say it's 100 days it's going to take to do this, to make

262
00:13:19,635 --> 00:13:21,435
this change, bring that to the producer.

263
00:13:21,815 --> 00:13:25,077
they will so appreciate that you've done it in terms that they can understand.

264
00:13:25,557 --> 00:13:26,637
You may get the answer of,

265
00:13:26,997 --> 00:13:28,238
well, okay, 100 extra days,

266
00:13:28,278 --> 00:13:29,498
we can do that, it's in the budget,

267
00:13:29,619 --> 00:13:33,640
but at least you will have a reasonable amount of time to do

268
00:13:33,700 --> 00:13:35,901
the thing that you need to do to make the change and

269
00:13:35,941 --> 00:13:38,902
the producer will expect a reasonable outcome from you.

270
00:13:39,522 --> 00:13:40,983
On the other hand, they might say, oh my God,

271
00:13:41,023 --> 00:13:42,984
we can't take 100 extra days,

272
00:13:43,084 --> 00:13:44,825
and then you might even not have to make the change.

273
00:13:44,885 --> 00:13:48,066
So push back, but do it in the language of the producers.

274
00:13:48,806 --> 00:13:51,728
Numbers are really helpful when you're working with something that is normally

275
00:13:52,529 --> 00:13:53,890
quantitative versus qualitative.

276
00:13:54,511 --> 00:13:57,933
If you can put it in terms that, as George has said very well, that producers can

277
00:13:57,953 --> 00:14:01,456
understand, then you're going to have a lot more support to say, we need to do

278
00:14:01,516 --> 00:14:05,600
this X amount of work, because people can look at writing and say, oh, but you just

279
00:14:05,620 --> 00:14:06,440
need to redo the script.

280
00:14:06,761 --> 00:14:07,561
That's five minutes.

281
00:14:07,681 --> 00:14:08,702
You know, it's going to be fine.

282
00:14:09,203 --> 00:14:10,704
It's just the time it takes to type it in.

283
00:14:11,064 --> 00:14:12,065
That's it, it's really just,

284
00:14:12,145 --> 00:14:13,746
I mean, you don't have to search the letters out

285
00:14:13,786 --> 00:14:15,808
individually and put them on the screen.

286
00:14:15,828 --> 00:14:17,289
You're not making a ransom note here.

287
00:14:18,330 --> 00:14:20,571
So they tend to think of it in terms of that

288
00:14:20,631 --> 00:14:22,033
and they don't tend to think of it in terms of,

289
00:14:22,113 --> 00:14:24,675
oh well, if I had to redo my level from the start,

290
00:14:25,055 --> 00:14:27,397
okay, that's three months worth of work, right?

291
00:14:27,477 --> 00:14:30,179
So having that ability to talk to producers

292
00:14:30,299 --> 00:14:32,160
is an excellent skill, I'm glad that George raised it.

293
00:14:33,822 --> 00:14:34,943
And Chris, would you like to answer?

294
00:14:35,203 --> 00:14:37,625
Oh yeah, so yeah, I'd be the third person to say that,

295
00:14:37,665 --> 00:14:39,627
you know, metrics will win a lot of arguments for you

296
00:14:39,667 --> 00:14:41,489
with production and getting the game done on time.

297
00:14:42,149 --> 00:14:45,612
However, I've often found that when level design

298
00:14:45,672 --> 00:14:47,694
and system design is still in flux,

299
00:14:47,834 --> 00:14:49,935
there's still a number of core elements

300
00:14:49,995 --> 00:14:51,156
I can always still count on.

301
00:14:51,717 --> 00:14:54,659
So I gear a lot of my writing efforts to making sure

302
00:14:54,739 --> 00:14:56,961
that at least the writing is supporting that,

303
00:14:56,981 --> 00:14:58,442
and that's very unlikely to change.

304
00:14:59,503 --> 00:15:03,164
What George was saying about pushback when certain things are in flux,

305
00:15:03,644 --> 00:15:07,065
I think it's also important to ask why things are changing.

306
00:15:07,085 --> 00:15:12,066
Because sometimes I've been on projects where people have been looking at it too long

307
00:15:12,546 --> 00:15:15,546
and they start getting bored with it and they feel it has to change

308
00:15:16,027 --> 00:15:19,187
before a player has ever seen the gameplay experience at all.

309
00:15:19,227 --> 00:15:21,368
And that's the absolute wrong thing to do.

310
00:15:22,268 --> 00:15:26,432
That's when you bring a focus test in to show them that people are really excited about what they're doing

311
00:15:26,793 --> 00:15:29,796
and show them these things don't need to change simply for the sake of boredom.

312
00:15:30,617 --> 00:15:31,958
But to actually get some helpful advice,

313
00:15:32,779 --> 00:15:37,664
when doing writing for RPGs especially, what I try and do is create

314
00:15:38,385 --> 00:15:41,629
critical paths and quest lines that involve floating NPCs.

315
00:15:42,229 --> 00:15:44,010
And these are NPCs that you can move to

316
00:15:44,070 --> 00:15:47,171
just about any map, anywhere, and the quest will still work.

317
00:15:47,251 --> 00:15:48,911
So even if the level design is changing,

318
00:15:49,292 --> 00:15:50,692
even if systems might be different,

319
00:15:50,732 --> 00:15:52,573
you can place these NPCs anywhere

320
00:15:52,633 --> 00:15:54,753
and still maintain a coherent quest line.

321
00:15:56,074 --> 00:15:58,235
Yeah, removing the narrative from the actual level flow

322
00:15:58,295 --> 00:15:59,235
can sometimes be helpful.

323
00:15:59,735 --> 00:16:01,956
Reintegrating it is also very useful though.

324
00:16:01,996 --> 00:16:03,256
You need to have consistency

325
00:16:03,276 --> 00:16:04,297
between the narrative and the level.

326
00:16:04,357 --> 00:16:06,257
Otherwise, that's complicated.

327
00:16:10,227 --> 00:16:11,147
We'll move on to the next one.

328
00:16:11,227 --> 00:16:14,390
So what do you do when the game's story gets re-scoped

329
00:16:14,450 --> 00:16:15,711
during the latter part of production

330
00:16:15,851 --> 00:16:17,472
and how do you integrate the necessary changes

331
00:16:17,512 --> 00:16:19,073
continuing on from the same theme?

332
00:16:19,713 --> 00:16:21,234
Well, as Chris was saying,

333
00:16:21,895 --> 00:16:25,057
it's very useful to develop a critical path document

334
00:16:25,758 --> 00:16:28,439
with the floating NPCs who can move places

335
00:16:29,040 --> 00:16:32,482
because chances are good your game will get re-scoped.

336
00:16:33,925 --> 00:16:40,748
we're all very ambitious storytellers. And ambition is frequently the enemy of reality.

337
00:16:42,209 --> 00:16:47,831
So you need to, if you have a critical path document with your flow chart and you're

338
00:16:48,092 --> 00:16:52,694
essentially figuring out what it is that you need to accomplish in the story, you can start

339
00:16:52,774 --> 00:16:57,416
pushing things toward the front because your game will get re-scoped unless you have done

340
00:16:57,476 --> 00:17:00,558
just such a masterful job of early production.

341
00:17:01,451 --> 00:17:04,212
which, you know, if you have, please introduce me to your producer.

342
00:17:06,033 --> 00:17:11,575
But this is actually a good opportunity for you because it allows you to re-examine the

343
00:17:11,595 --> 00:17:15,836
story, it allows you to re-examine the structure of the whole thing, and you can start re-pacing

344
00:17:16,176 --> 00:17:22,159
and you can start re-scoping and pushing everything into a more compact, more easily digestible

345
00:17:22,259 --> 00:17:26,480
story because, let's face it, we are writers and we tend to write long.

346
00:17:28,732 --> 00:17:30,456
Sometimes edits make a script so much better

347
00:17:30,496 --> 00:17:32,000
and you didn't even know that you needed to do that.

348
00:17:32,020 --> 00:17:34,105
I actually like re-scoping for that reason.

349
00:17:34,145 --> 00:17:35,067
Sometimes it allows you to go,

350
00:17:35,388 --> 00:17:36,711
oh, I didn't need that to begin with.

351
00:17:40,857 --> 00:17:42,518
Chris, did you have something to say on the?

352
00:17:42,558 --> 00:17:43,958
Yeah, with rescoping.

353
00:17:44,478 --> 00:17:46,279
So it's a lot of what we discussed before,

354
00:17:46,359 --> 00:17:48,920
but generally whenever doing narrative work for a game,

355
00:17:48,980 --> 00:17:51,680
I usually prioritize everything into A, critical path,

356
00:17:52,201 --> 00:17:53,921
B, this would be nice to have,

357
00:17:53,961 --> 00:17:56,662
and the player would certainly probably slightly miss it

358
00:17:56,682 --> 00:17:57,282
if it wasn't there,

359
00:17:57,322 --> 00:17:59,163
and C, priority is just like gravy stuff

360
00:17:59,183 --> 00:18:00,223
that the player would probably love,

361
00:18:00,263 --> 00:18:01,683
but they wouldn't miss it if it wasn't there.

362
00:18:02,744 --> 00:18:06,864
So I break all the tasks into those elements and then as things need to get downscoped

363
00:18:06,884 --> 00:18:13,686
I drop the C elements and then the B elements, hopefully not the B elements, but I keep that priority system in mind.

364
00:18:14,966 --> 00:18:21,448
When re-scoping I also ask why it's being re-scoped because I need to understand

365
00:18:22,408 --> 00:18:28,069
what material has already been done, what I can count on, and what I shouldn't drop from the story

366
00:18:28,309 --> 00:18:30,530
that actually is already done and I can make use of.

367
00:18:30,550 --> 00:18:32,210
Go to Beadaholique.com for all of your beading supply needs!

368
00:18:32,630 --> 00:18:34,651
Generally, whenever anything's being re-scoped,

369
00:18:35,372 --> 00:18:38,093
in addition to that floating NPC idea I mentioned before,

370
00:18:38,673 --> 00:18:40,113
about halfway through production,

371
00:18:40,193 --> 00:18:45,015
writers aren't blind to the fact that environment art

372
00:18:45,075 --> 00:18:46,596
might not be getting done, for example.

373
00:18:46,656 --> 00:18:48,497
So I actually start making a secret list

374
00:18:49,097 --> 00:18:50,598
of all the environments that we already have done

375
00:18:50,638 --> 00:18:52,958
for the game and how we can change them slightly

376
00:18:53,319 --> 00:18:55,519
and still maintain new gameplay spaces.

377
00:18:55,580 --> 00:18:57,200
Like, hey, we can still use Rome,

378
00:18:57,700 --> 00:18:58,741
but it'll be Rome at night.

379
00:18:59,501 --> 00:19:00,381
That'll help you, won't it?

380
00:19:01,298 --> 00:19:02,439
And the story goes on.

381
00:19:02,459 --> 00:19:06,181
But yeah, that's just a few techniques I use.

382
00:19:06,221 --> 00:19:09,003
Yeah, some of the story stuff is actually pretty easy

383
00:19:09,043 --> 00:19:09,924
to adjust as well.

384
00:19:10,004 --> 00:19:12,125
And you can throw little bits of dialogue in.

385
00:19:12,826 --> 00:19:16,308
It's important to know what bits of the story

386
00:19:16,428 --> 00:19:18,189
are important to be delivered when.

387
00:19:19,170 --> 00:19:21,031
And so if you can just move that

388
00:19:21,271 --> 00:19:24,013
or even just quickly adjust a small bit of dialogue,

389
00:19:24,033 --> 00:19:27,215
that really helps in the whole re-scope process.

390
00:19:27,615 --> 00:19:29,356
But Chris's process is actually better.

391
00:19:30,569 --> 00:19:32,390
But he did raise a really good point that you need to know

392
00:19:32,530 --> 00:19:34,892
why it's being re-scoped because you need to tailor

393
00:19:34,932 --> 00:19:37,913
the story to what the re-scoping needs.

394
00:19:38,014 --> 00:19:39,254
There is nothing better than like,

395
00:19:39,354 --> 00:19:40,435
oh, environment art's behind.

396
00:19:40,475 --> 00:19:42,736
Like, okay, well I can fix this if they do 50 new levels.

397
00:19:42,756 --> 00:19:44,718
And they're like, that doesn't help us at all.

398
00:19:45,278 --> 00:19:46,519
But you can put an amazing story in there.

399
00:19:46,539 --> 00:19:47,159
There's so much space.

400
00:19:49,472 --> 00:19:54,118
But in terms of that, we are normally talking with producers when we're talking about re-scoping.

401
00:19:54,759 --> 00:19:59,405
And it's very important to have a producer who understands the needs of narrative versus the needs of other departments.

402
00:20:00,287 --> 00:20:04,492
And so I think we all have an opinion on what qualities writers need in their producers.

403
00:20:06,835 --> 00:20:07,656
Casual murder.

404
00:20:09,942 --> 00:20:15,863
Well, okay, so I've had a lot of producers and I think I've been lucky in that I've had pretty

405
00:20:15,903 --> 00:20:22,245
much all good ones. But I can say there's been a few that were absolutely stellar and I think the

406
00:20:22,285 --> 00:20:31,287
thing that made them stand apart was a shared passion. They are the ones that get mad on your

407
00:20:31,347 --> 00:20:31,827
behalf.

408
00:20:33,100 --> 00:20:36,542
So if I, and an understanding of design does help too.

409
00:20:36,622 --> 00:20:41,464
So if you are out there and looking to be a writer's

410
00:20:41,504 --> 00:20:46,866
producer, care about what they have, definitely give them

411
00:20:46,926 --> 00:20:48,067
feedback on the story.

412
00:20:48,427 --> 00:20:49,807
And that doesn't necessarily mean.

413
00:20:51,188 --> 00:20:54,190
stop them from brainstorming, for example.

414
00:20:54,250 --> 00:20:55,852
But definitely if they're seeking feedback,

415
00:20:55,872 --> 00:20:56,612
get them feedback.

416
00:20:56,652 --> 00:20:59,114
If they have design questions, get them answers.

417
00:20:59,775 --> 00:21:01,096
Get passionate on their behalf

418
00:21:01,156 --> 00:21:02,437
and help them solve the problems

419
00:21:02,477 --> 00:21:04,018
that are stopping them from moving forward.

420
00:21:06,503 --> 00:21:10,505
So I'm going to answer this one from a couple of different perspectives.

421
00:21:10,766 --> 00:21:14,688
The first perspective is from an indie, a small team.

422
00:21:15,528 --> 00:21:19,611
What you want most from a producer there is flexibility and range.

423
00:21:20,051 --> 00:21:22,092
You want somebody who knows how to do art.

424
00:21:22,132 --> 00:21:24,514
You want somebody who knows how to do programming.

425
00:21:24,534 --> 00:21:27,996
You want somebody who knows how to do sound, so that they are able to reach out and get

426
00:21:28,036 --> 00:21:32,599
into each discipline and communicate with people effectively and step in to fill the

427
00:21:32,619 --> 00:21:33,699
gaps that are necessary.

428
00:21:34,980 --> 00:21:40,043
If you're talking a larger scale game, though, what you need is somebody who understands

429
00:21:40,384 --> 00:21:46,968
scope, budget, and basically all the metrics that go into keeping a game on time and on

430
00:21:47,048 --> 00:21:51,250
track. Somebody who knows how to communicate both with upper management and with the

431
00:21:51,330 --> 00:21:57,154
lower ranks, that is crucial. Because if there is a blockage in any one of those things,

432
00:21:57,695 --> 00:21:58,635
you're headed down.

433
00:22:00,540 --> 00:22:02,742
And as Chris said, being able to put things by priority

434
00:22:02,762 --> 00:22:05,364
and having a producer who understands writing priority

435
00:22:05,404 --> 00:22:07,346
as opposed to level up priority

436
00:22:07,706 --> 00:22:09,347
makes a really big difference when you're able to say,

437
00:22:09,407 --> 00:22:11,109
okay, but I really, really, really need to do

438
00:22:11,149 --> 00:22:13,310
this conversation that seems like it's not important at all

439
00:22:13,350 --> 00:22:15,372
because otherwise the whole narrative falls down.

440
00:22:15,832 --> 00:22:16,773
Having a producer who goes,

441
00:22:16,973 --> 00:22:18,154
okay, we're gonna make this work

442
00:22:18,695 --> 00:22:20,036
and being a person who fights for you

443
00:22:20,056 --> 00:22:21,917
and advocates for the things that you want to do

444
00:22:21,957 --> 00:22:24,359
with the story versus the creative direction

445
00:22:24,399 --> 00:22:26,521
and everything like that, they're normally a mediator.

446
00:22:27,041 --> 00:22:29,142
if they're working with you and for you,

447
00:22:29,523 --> 00:22:32,124
they're mediating between all the other inputs

448
00:22:32,144 --> 00:22:33,165
that are coming in, and in fact,

449
00:22:33,205 --> 00:22:35,786
they're helping you talk to the other departments as well.

450
00:22:36,327 --> 00:22:38,368
And I wanted to say that saying it's a person

451
00:22:38,408 --> 00:22:40,729
who gets mad on your behalf is a really excellent way

452
00:22:40,789 --> 00:22:42,730
to look at the best producers that I've worked with.

453
00:22:43,171 --> 00:22:44,732
They're the ones who allow me to sit in the room

454
00:22:44,772 --> 00:22:47,353
and be the cool, calm, quiet, collected writer

455
00:22:47,373 --> 00:22:49,054
who's like, oh yes, I see what you're doing there.

456
00:22:49,074 --> 00:22:51,315
And they're the one who's going, no, this is unacceptable,

457
00:22:51,335 --> 00:22:52,916
we're not doing this, it's a waste of time.

458
00:22:52,976 --> 00:22:53,837
And I just get to sit there and go,

459
00:22:53,857 --> 00:22:55,098
hee hee hee, this is fantastic.

460
00:22:55,858 --> 00:23:00,703
So, having someone who can fight for you, and there's a bit of an assumption that writers

461
00:23:00,723 --> 00:23:03,826
tend to be dramatic, whether that's true or not.

462
00:23:05,667 --> 00:23:10,231
So being able to be calm and collected is a real privilege when working with a good

463
00:23:10,272 --> 00:23:10,772
producer.

464
00:23:11,513 --> 00:23:15,556
It tends to get your point across much more frequently than it might otherwise.

465
00:23:20,671 --> 00:23:22,273
What qualities do writers need in their producers?

466
00:23:22,513 --> 00:23:24,635
Oh, I'm part of this question too?

467
00:23:24,735 --> 00:23:26,617
Wow, I'm going to be really undermining.

468
00:23:27,278 --> 00:23:29,460
I actually don't like it when a producer gets emotional.

469
00:23:29,900 --> 00:23:32,783
I actually like it when they firmly defend a position

470
00:23:32,823 --> 00:23:34,105
and they use metrics to defend it,

471
00:23:34,205 --> 00:23:38,569
because I've often found that if a producer gets too emotional about something,

472
00:23:38,609 --> 00:23:41,051
sometimes people are afraid to bring up problems with them

473
00:23:41,091 --> 00:23:42,233
because they're afraid of the reaction.

474
00:23:43,373 --> 00:23:46,615
So, whenever I work with producers, I'm always like,

475
00:23:46,655 --> 00:23:48,516
you know what, just pretend like you're in Dragnet

476
00:23:48,996 --> 00:23:51,717
and just, you know, be the guy who just wants the facts

477
00:23:52,177 --> 00:23:53,658
and spout some facts back to me,

478
00:23:53,678 --> 00:23:56,459
and I'll reach a compromise that will usually involve me

479
00:23:56,679 --> 00:23:57,240
cutting my work.

480
00:23:57,620 --> 00:23:58,600
And I will understand that

481
00:23:58,660 --> 00:23:59,921
because you're not being emotional right now.

482
00:24:02,857 --> 00:24:04,938
So I'm going to say ability to know your people.

483
00:24:06,659 --> 00:24:08,381
A good producer, at least in my opinion,

484
00:24:08,741 --> 00:24:11,343
has an ability to know each writer's strengths, weaknesses,

485
00:24:11,403 --> 00:24:13,064
and what they need to do their best work.

486
00:24:14,025 --> 00:24:16,947
And probably the best producer I've ever worked with,

487
00:24:16,967 --> 00:24:19,709
a guy named Kevin Saunders, who just about all of us know,

488
00:24:19,729 --> 00:24:20,590
or I think all of us know.

489
00:24:21,970 --> 00:24:27,111
He, on the first project I worked with him on, made it his business to observe me and

490
00:24:27,211 --> 00:24:29,632
figure out what he could do to make me my most productive.

491
00:24:29,832 --> 00:24:32,432
And one of the things about me is I am super distractible.

492
00:24:32,992 --> 00:24:36,793
So if I'm sitting in a room, there's like a bunch of people talking, yeah, it's like

493
00:24:36,813 --> 00:24:37,013
that.

494
00:24:37,033 --> 00:24:38,233
I just lost.

495
00:24:38,934 --> 00:24:42,914
So, and people coming in and out, lots of noise, I will get very little done.

496
00:24:43,895 --> 00:24:48,816
So he observed that about me, and then he, behind the scenes, worked to get me my own

497
00:24:48,836 --> 00:24:49,716
little private office.

498
00:24:50,176 --> 00:24:52,237
And it was not like some spectacular office,

499
00:24:52,297 --> 00:24:54,438
but I loved it because I could shut the door

500
00:24:54,778 --> 00:24:57,679
and I could focus and I got so much done.

501
00:24:58,400 --> 00:25:00,801
According to Kevin's metrics, my productivity doubled

502
00:25:01,281 --> 00:25:03,182
just as a result of that one change.

503
00:25:04,222 --> 00:25:07,044
So, and I am certain that that game,

504
00:25:07,084 --> 00:25:08,844
the writing on that game would not have gotten done

505
00:25:08,884 --> 00:25:10,145
and certainly would not have gotten done

506
00:25:10,165 --> 00:25:12,726
at that quality level if he had not done that.

507
00:25:13,226 --> 00:25:15,107
So that's a big argument for producers

508
00:25:15,147 --> 00:25:17,028
who can understand their people

509
00:25:17,128 --> 00:25:19,269
and know what is gonna make them do their best work.

510
00:25:20,351 --> 00:25:21,832
That's an excellent segue, George,

511
00:25:21,872 --> 00:25:23,573
in terms of getting to know new people.

512
00:25:23,933 --> 00:25:25,754
How do you go about mentoring new writers?

513
00:25:26,334 --> 00:25:30,116
What's the best way to instruct a veteran writer

514
00:25:30,196 --> 00:25:31,657
to mentor a new writer?

515
00:25:32,497 --> 00:25:33,437
You want me or Chris first?

516
00:25:33,738 --> 00:25:34,198
Yeah, you can go.

517
00:25:34,238 --> 00:25:34,338
Me?

518
00:25:34,438 --> 00:25:35,438
OK.

519
00:25:35,699 --> 00:25:38,780
So a couple of people on this panel

520
00:25:38,800 --> 00:25:40,281
will know these things about me.

521
00:25:41,341 --> 00:25:43,242
So the first thing I would do is,

522
00:25:46,175 --> 00:25:50,719
make sure that you are giving writers a lot of feedback.

523
00:25:51,881 --> 00:25:54,583
In the initial dialogues that are coming in,

524
00:25:54,724 --> 00:25:56,726
when you've got a new writer that you've hired on,

525
00:25:57,246 --> 00:25:59,588
make sure that you're giving a ton of feedback.

526
00:25:59,909 --> 00:26:02,652
What I will do, actually Gavin experienced this from me,

527
00:26:04,493 --> 00:26:06,315
I mean, he knows what I'm talking about.

528
00:26:06,836 --> 00:26:08,718
The first couple dialogues that come in,

529
00:26:08,818 --> 00:26:11,481
I will read every word, I will read every single node,

530
00:26:12,142 --> 00:26:13,843
and I will give feedback, if necessary,

531
00:26:13,944 --> 00:26:15,505
on every single note of dialogue.

532
00:26:15,585 --> 00:26:18,909
I'm somewhat notorious for my multi-page reviews

533
00:26:19,089 --> 00:26:20,391
of people's dialogues.

534
00:26:21,691 --> 00:26:26,113
But it's really important on those first few dialogues that come in,

535
00:26:26,713 --> 00:26:29,814
because it sort of sets the standard for the rest of the person's work.

536
00:26:29,874 --> 00:26:33,435
So like if you can get them to that level of quality that you need very early on,

537
00:26:34,215 --> 00:26:35,436
then they're going to continue with that.

538
00:26:35,476 --> 00:26:39,757
And then I'll dial it back once the writer knows or has a pretty good sense of what they need to do.

539
00:26:40,077 --> 00:26:43,738
I'll dial it back a little bit, although I still do try to read just about everything that comes in.

540
00:26:44,779 --> 00:26:49,222
Another thing to keep in mind is try to stagger the introduction of new writers.

541
00:26:49,542 --> 00:26:53,065
So if you have any control over how many people are coming on the project,

542
00:26:53,445 --> 00:26:57,048
six writers at once, like if you're trying to review dialogues in depth

543
00:26:57,068 --> 00:26:59,549
from six different new writers on a project, you're going to die.

544
00:27:00,010 --> 00:27:04,313
So what you want to do instead is try to get one or two dialogues at a time,

545
00:27:04,593 --> 00:27:07,395
or one or two writers at a time, review their dialogues in detail,

546
00:27:07,755 --> 00:27:12,239
and then once those guys are up to speed, then bring in another one or two writers after that,

547
00:27:12,879 --> 00:27:13,800
which will help you out a lot.

548
00:27:16,069 --> 00:27:19,032
I used to do postmortems for my managers without their knowledge.

549
00:27:20,593 --> 00:27:24,317
And I would take those things to heart and go, you know what, if I'm ever in that position,

550
00:27:24,357 --> 00:27:26,219
I will not do any of these things.

551
00:27:26,419 --> 00:27:32,685
One favorite thing was a fun technique called give a person a lack of expectations and then

552
00:27:32,865 --> 00:27:34,307
also give them negative reinforcement.

553
00:27:34,587 --> 00:27:34,787
So

554
00:27:35,007 --> 00:27:39,070
But what I like to do with new writers is quite clearly lay out the expectations that

555
00:27:39,090 --> 00:27:40,230
I have for them for the position.

556
00:27:41,511 --> 00:27:45,954
Also I try and make sure there's already a standards guide and a style guide set up for

557
00:27:45,994 --> 00:27:46,974
writing for the project.

558
00:27:47,495 --> 00:27:51,797
And then Carbine actually had a really cool technique for bringing in their new level

559
00:27:51,817 --> 00:27:55,639
designers and world builders where they'd give them a series of very small, simple tasks.

560
00:27:56,120 --> 00:27:58,301
Here's how you implement a small dialogue into the game.

561
00:27:58,341 --> 00:28:00,123
Here's how you implement an inventory item.

562
00:28:00,163 --> 00:28:02,044
Here's how you write the description for it.

563
00:28:02,444 --> 00:28:04,005
And these are all very small tasks,

564
00:28:04,105 --> 00:28:06,487
but it helped build up the person's knowledge

565
00:28:06,507 --> 00:28:08,769
of the pipeline in terms of how to get narrative

566
00:28:08,789 --> 00:28:09,389
into the game.

567
00:28:11,791 --> 00:28:15,153
For veteran writers that are mentoring new writers,

568
00:28:17,579 --> 00:28:21,242
We had an unusual system where sometimes veteran writers would forget

569
00:28:21,402 --> 00:28:24,025
that they were once new writers, and then they would never want

570
00:28:24,045 --> 00:28:25,947
to accept new writers or give them a chance

571
00:28:26,047 --> 00:28:28,950
because they couldn't see how that person could ever possibly get

572
00:28:28,970 --> 00:28:31,473
to their level, which is a bunch of crap.

573
00:28:32,214 --> 00:28:35,197
So what I like to do is like when you assign someone

574
00:28:35,217 --> 00:28:37,619
to a mentorship position, you remind them that, look,

575
00:28:38,240 --> 00:28:44,342
You know what, you got to the level you were by taking it in stages, so please approach it in the same way with the new writer here.

576
00:28:45,182 --> 00:28:51,224
And also, don't be afraid to think you might be insulting them by giving them too much information.

577
00:28:52,664 --> 00:28:57,366
Give them everything that you think is even the most basic technique about narrative design,

578
00:28:57,806 --> 00:28:59,687
and make sure you're explaining to them thoroughly.

579
00:29:02,988 --> 00:29:05,310
why you're telling them about this particular technique.

580
00:29:05,350 --> 00:29:08,252
And then I also tell the new writers that, hey, you know what?

581
00:29:08,272 --> 00:29:09,253
They might cross the line.

582
00:29:09,273 --> 00:29:10,754
They might be over-explaining stuff.

583
00:29:10,774 --> 00:29:12,816
But they're doing it in your best interest.

584
00:29:13,436 --> 00:29:15,057
And what George was saying about feedback,

585
00:29:16,158 --> 00:29:19,441
generally I try and give feedback very, very rapidly at the outset.

586
00:29:19,901 --> 00:29:22,583
And then I start backing off over the course of the project

587
00:29:22,703 --> 00:29:24,944
once I see that one particular narrative element

588
00:29:25,345 --> 00:29:27,986
or aesthetic is actually, seems pretty solid.

589
00:29:28,427 --> 00:29:29,968
Like it might be like a daily review,

590
00:29:30,008 --> 00:29:31,829
then a weekly review, then a monthly review,

591
00:29:31,949 --> 00:29:33,850
until I feel I can count on that person

592
00:29:34,211 --> 00:29:35,432
to deliver to expectations.

593
00:29:36,179 --> 00:29:37,960
And actually, Chris just reminded me, I got another one.

594
00:29:38,720 --> 00:29:42,182
Early on in the project, if you can have some example dialogues

595
00:29:42,202 --> 00:29:45,023
that you can give to new writers at exactly the level of quality

596
00:29:45,043 --> 00:29:47,184
that you want them to be, that is super helpful.

597
00:29:47,204 --> 00:29:49,845
Because a lot of other writers will, writers are very good at sort

598
00:29:49,865 --> 00:29:51,626
of hitting the mark that you give them early on.

599
00:29:51,706 --> 00:29:52,986
Yeah, actually examples are better

600
00:29:53,046 --> 00:29:54,507
than technical standards documents.

601
00:29:54,547 --> 00:29:55,427
Ideally, you want to have both.

602
00:29:58,204 --> 00:30:02,128
I think it's very important to have that feedback very early on as you say.

603
00:30:02,168 --> 00:30:06,912
It can be pretty confronting if you're a new writer coming into a studio to get pages and pages of feedback.

604
00:30:06,972 --> 00:30:12,277
But in the end, it's a fine balance between relearning your ego at the beginning of a project

605
00:30:12,337 --> 00:30:15,540
versus eventually coming to the place where you can fight the battles that you want to fight.

606
00:30:15,780 --> 00:30:19,243
And that's what I enjoy about mentoring writers is seeing them at the beginning and saying,

607
00:30:19,283 --> 00:30:19,363
OK,

608
00:30:20,100 --> 00:30:22,362
here are the things that need to change and here is why.

609
00:30:22,382 --> 00:30:23,943
I'm not gonna tell you how to change them,

610
00:30:24,003 --> 00:30:25,764
but I want you to change them and come back to me.

611
00:30:26,164 --> 00:30:28,605
And then tell me why you think we needed to do that.

612
00:30:28,965 --> 00:30:31,086
And tell me what you think this brought to your writing

613
00:30:31,527 --> 00:30:33,868
so that they can start examining their own process

614
00:30:33,988 --> 00:30:37,010
and then they can turn that inward the whole time.

615
00:30:37,550 --> 00:30:39,351
And as both George and Chris have said,

616
00:30:39,391 --> 00:30:40,632
then you move forward and give feedback

617
00:30:40,672 --> 00:30:42,813
less and less frequently until you get to the point

618
00:30:42,833 --> 00:30:44,054
where you're mentoring someone and you say,

619
00:30:44,394 --> 00:30:45,915
I think this should change and they say no.

620
00:30:45,935 --> 00:30:47,235
And you go, okay.

621
00:30:48,416 --> 00:30:49,257
And that's a wonderful moment.

622
00:30:51,594 --> 00:30:52,996
You guys have anything?

623
00:30:53,216 --> 00:30:54,498
Okay.

624
00:30:54,518 --> 00:30:57,402
And then we'll move on to a very similar question.

625
00:30:57,442 --> 00:30:58,924
A new writer is assigned to your project,

626
00:30:59,305 --> 00:31:00,967
but the first question they have is to question

627
00:31:00,987 --> 00:31:02,009
the premise of the game.

628
00:31:02,510 --> 00:31:03,471
How do you mitigate this?

629
00:31:04,292 --> 00:31:04,973
We all wanna jump in?

630
00:31:05,865 --> 00:31:09,487
So you may have gathered that I enjoy getting feedback

631
00:31:09,507 --> 00:31:10,127
from other people.

632
00:31:11,188 --> 00:31:13,769
So I would say you want to gather the feedback

633
00:31:13,789 --> 00:31:14,689
from these new writers.

634
00:31:14,909 --> 00:31:16,970
You listen carefully to them, and you

635
00:31:17,010 --> 00:31:19,371
try and figure out what it is exactly that they

636
00:31:19,391 --> 00:31:20,252
are trying to tell you.

637
00:31:21,932 --> 00:31:24,173
But on the other hand, Stephen King

638
00:31:24,273 --> 00:31:27,915
once said, if you give 10 people a piece of work

639
00:31:27,975 --> 00:31:29,896
and they all comment on the same thing,

640
00:31:30,456 --> 00:31:33,738
you know you've got a problem with that thing. But if they all comment on ten different things

641
00:31:33,998 --> 00:31:38,621
then you're probably good to go. So the important thing is to listen carefully. You get their

642
00:31:38,641 --> 00:31:43,364
feedback because a new set of eyes is always useful. It's always going to help you hone

643
00:31:44,004 --> 00:31:49,608
what the message of your story is or what it is you're trying to convey. At the same

644
00:31:49,708 --> 00:31:56,012
time if this new writer is unwilling to see the direction of the game and the game is

645
00:31:56,092 --> 00:31:59,254
already well into production and they are unable to get on board.

646
00:32:00,162 --> 00:32:01,824
then you've got to get your producer involved

647
00:32:02,025 --> 00:32:03,507
and you've got to start talking to the producer

648
00:32:03,567 --> 00:32:04,288
and it's a sad thing.

649
00:32:04,608 --> 00:32:06,351
This game has fundamental flaws.

650
00:32:06,591 --> 00:32:07,372
That's right.

651
00:32:08,234 --> 00:32:09,175
Please identify them.

652
00:32:09,315 --> 00:32:10,917
Okay, those are not flaws, those are intentional.

653
00:32:11,578 --> 00:32:12,239
Will not fix.

654
00:32:13,630 --> 00:32:15,432
Do you guys hear a spaceship outside?

655
00:32:15,592 --> 00:32:17,534
Yeah, there's a...

656
00:32:17,574 --> 00:32:18,715
It's just building to a crescendo.

657
00:32:18,775 --> 00:32:19,916
I think it landed, we're good.

658
00:32:20,496 --> 00:32:21,077
Okay, good.

659
00:32:21,457 --> 00:32:23,359
But no, bringing on new writers is always fun,

660
00:32:23,399 --> 00:32:24,159
it's always exciting.

661
00:32:24,179 --> 00:32:26,421
And when new writers, you know,

662
00:32:27,242 --> 00:32:28,783
I would hope that they would question, you know,

663
00:32:28,823 --> 00:32:29,784
the premise of the game,

664
00:32:29,864 --> 00:32:31,946
because it's in questioning that we learn.

665
00:32:32,647 --> 00:32:34,408
And if they are not questioning,

666
00:32:34,508 --> 00:32:36,490
then they're just collecting a paycheck.

667
00:32:37,010 --> 00:32:39,633
And I want people to be involved in the process and invested.

668
00:32:40,046 --> 00:32:41,527
And if they're not actually asking questions,

669
00:32:41,567 --> 00:32:43,387
that doesn't mean they're not asking them to themselves.

670
00:32:43,767 --> 00:32:46,048
So it's always better to expose the questions they have

671
00:32:46,088 --> 00:32:47,549
and then you can work with them to solve it,

672
00:32:47,969 --> 00:32:50,170
rather than letting them go and work on their own

673
00:32:50,210 --> 00:32:51,511
and then perhaps being uncomfortable.

674
00:32:52,731 --> 00:32:55,072
Or even worse, going and working on their own

675
00:32:55,092 --> 00:32:56,172
and not actually getting the game.

676
00:32:56,853 --> 00:32:57,033
Yes.

677
00:32:59,774 --> 00:33:02,075
Okay, you're asked to write for an existing franchise.

678
00:33:02,115 --> 00:33:03,515
How do you go about inheriting it

679
00:33:03,555 --> 00:33:05,536
and how do you do justice while retaining your own voice?

680
00:33:05,556 --> 00:33:07,757
So, flip side, you're the new writer.

681
00:33:09,783 --> 00:33:09,983
Chris?

682
00:33:11,304 --> 00:33:13,845
So we had this challenge with the System Shock reboot

683
00:33:13,905 --> 00:33:15,846
and then other franchises I've worked with,

684
00:33:15,866 --> 00:33:17,627
whether it's like South Park or Star Wars.

685
00:33:18,948 --> 00:33:22,690
So the process we used with System Shock was, first off,

686
00:33:23,190 --> 00:33:25,371
put away your preconceived notions

687
00:33:25,431 --> 00:33:27,692
for where you think it should go instinctually.

688
00:33:27,753 --> 00:33:29,553
Just shelve that for a little while.

689
00:33:31,527 --> 00:33:36,529
The best way to approach it we found was just go talk to the original creators, see what

690
00:33:36,549 --> 00:33:39,730
their intentions were for the project, what they were thinking about the time during the

691
00:33:39,770 --> 00:33:45,052
creation of the project, get their feedback, go through all their podcasts or any sort

692
00:33:45,092 --> 00:33:49,314
of let's plays they may have done, get a sense for any commentary they had about the original

693
00:33:49,354 --> 00:33:52,275
game, try and figure out if there's any ways you can incorporate any of that.

694
00:33:54,215 --> 00:33:56,757
And even though System Shock isn't the best example for this,

695
00:33:57,477 --> 00:34:00,820
Star Wars was where you basically want to make sure you know as much

696
00:34:01,080 --> 00:34:03,481
as possible about the franchise just

697
00:34:03,501 --> 00:34:05,763
so you know what's already been done within the confines

698
00:34:05,783 --> 00:34:06,363
of that franchise.

699
00:34:06,383 --> 00:34:09,465
And you're not just recycling some theme or some quest

700
00:34:09,485 --> 00:34:12,627
or even some storyline that, you know, maybe Dark Horse may have used

701
00:34:12,647 --> 00:34:14,048
or another video game may have used.

702
00:34:14,088 --> 00:34:17,390
It's important that you know as much as possible about that franchise.

703
00:34:19,171 --> 00:34:27,573
During that process, my experience has been that you're going to be left with a lot of questions and a lot of thoughts and a lot of inspiration for where you think things should go.

704
00:34:27,713 --> 00:34:34,995
And that's the moment you sort of find your voice in the franchise after you've established what the foundation is and what the parameters for the game is.

705
00:34:36,955 --> 00:34:38,356
Man, I don't know how to follow all that.

706
00:34:40,250 --> 00:34:45,933
Well, I'd say the only thing I could possibly add is definitely look for where you fit within

707
00:34:45,953 --> 00:34:46,634
the franchise.

708
00:34:47,174 --> 00:34:48,255
You were talking about Star Wars.

709
00:34:48,495 --> 00:34:51,617
I did a lot of Blizzard stuff.

710
00:34:52,578 --> 00:34:57,000
And you want to have an idea of what your style is, and you want to be able to apply

711
00:34:57,040 --> 00:34:59,782
that style to whatever it is you're working on.

712
00:35:00,302 --> 00:35:05,165
Because as writers and as creators, you need to stay passionate to do your best work.

713
00:35:05,245 --> 00:35:08,508
And if you feel like you have no voice of your own, you're fucked.

714
00:35:09,028 --> 00:35:10,691
You really are, because everything you turn out

715
00:35:10,711 --> 00:35:11,433
is gonna be garbage.

716
00:35:12,274 --> 00:35:14,980
So take your style, find out where it fits,

717
00:35:15,420 --> 00:35:16,603
find the story you wanna tell,

718
00:35:16,683 --> 00:35:18,747
find the way you wanna tell it, and have fun.

719
00:35:19,208 --> 00:35:19,749
Have lots of fun.

720
00:35:21,340 --> 00:35:23,322
I would say it's important to find the voice of the project

721
00:35:23,382 --> 00:35:25,263
and then as you say, see how your style fits in.

722
00:35:25,763 --> 00:35:27,705
So I have found it very valuable to look at things

